Exploration and Analysis of Student Exam Performance¶

Arjun Patel, Navreet Bajwa, Yash Upadhyay¶

Introduction¶

Exam performance for students in high school is crucial to their future success. For our final project, we chose a dataset from Kaggle titled "Student Alcohol Consumption" which contains data gathered from a survey of students from two schools in Portugal about their weekday and weekend alcohol consumption as well as many other general attributes such as highest level of education achieved by their mother and father, how many extracurricular activities they're involved in, weekly study time, whether they want to pursue higher education, and many more.

The objective of our project was to try to predict exam performance using variables that seemed most intuitively relevant like study time, whether they take extra paid classes or not, whether or not they want to pursue higher education, and number of absences. We also investigated some of the more interesting and less intuitive variables like alcohol consumption and whether or not they're in a romantic relationship.

Data Collection & Processing¶

We'll start by importing some necessary libraries and modules

Here is a link to our dataset: https://www.kaggle.com/uciml/student-alcohol-consumption/.
Our data collection process consists of simply loading in the csv file "student-mat.csv" in the dataset which contains information on students in a math course. However, we still have some tidying to do as part of our data processing. After manually inspecting the columns contained in the csv file, we decided on which data we wanted to focus on for our analysis and which data we would discard. The column variables we decided to keep are:

  • student's sex (binary: 'F' - female or 'M' - male)
  • age - student's age (numeric: from 15 to 22)
  • Pstatus - parent's cohabitation status (binary: 'T' - living together or 'A' - apart)
  • Medu - mother's education (numeric: 0 - none, 1 - primary education (4th grade), 2 5th to 9th grade, 3 secondary education or 4 higher education)
  • Fedu - father's education (numeric: 0 - none, 1 - primary education (4th grade), 2 5th to 9th grade, 3 secondary education or 4 higher education)
  • studytime - weekly study time (numeric: 1 - <2 hours, 2 - 2 to 5 hours, 3 - 5 to 10 hours, or 4 - >10 hours)
  • failures - number of past class failures (numeric: n if 1<=n<3, else 4)
  • paid - extra paid classes within the course subject (Math or Portuguese) (binary: yes or no)
  • activities - extra-curricular activities (binary: yes or no)
  • higher - wants to take higher education (binary: yes or no)
  • internet - Internet access at home (binary: yes or no)
  • romantic - with a romantic relationship (binary: yes or no)
  • famrel - quality of family relationships (numeric: from 1 - very bad to 5 - excellent)
  • freetime - free time after school (numeric: from 1 - very low to 5 - very high)
  • goout - going out with friends (numeric: from 1 - very low to 5 - very high)
  • Dalc - workday alcohol consumption (numeric: from 1 - very low to 5 - very high)
  • Walc - weekend alcohol consumption (numeric: from 1 - very low to 5 - very high)
  • absences - number of school absences (numeric: from 0 to 93)
  • G1 - first period grade (numeric: from 0 to 20)
  • G2 - second period grade (numeric: from 0 to 20)
  • G3 - final grade (numeric: from 0 to 20, output target)

    We dropped the rest of the columns and added three columns. One with their average grade from G1, G2 and G3, one with their average alcohol consumption using workday and weekend alcohol consumption, and one with their parent's education aggregated as an average of their mother and father's education levels.
    We also added buckets for absences rather than keeping the numeric value for absences
In [4]:
tidy_data = pd.read_csv("student-mat.csv")
tidy_data = tidy_data.drop(['school','address','famsize','Mjob','Fjob','reason','guardian',
                'traveltime','schoolsup','famsup','nursery','health'], axis=1)
for i,row in tidy_data.iterrows():
    tidy_data.at[i,'Avg_Alc_Consumption'] = float((row['Dalc'] + row['Walc'])/2)
    tidy_data.at[i,'Parent_Education'] = float((row['Medu'] + row['Fedu'])/2)
    tidy_data.at[i,'Average_Score'] = float((row['G1']+row['G2']+row['G3'])/3)

tidy_data = tidy_data.drop(['Dalc','Walc','Medu', 'Fedu', 'G1', 'G2', 'G3'], axis=1)

absencebins=[0,5,10,20,25,30]
labels=[0,1,2,3,4]
tidy_data['absences'] = pd.cut(tidy_data['absences'], bins=absencebins, labels=labels, include_lowest=True)
tidy_data['absences'] = tidy_data['absences'].cat.codes
tidy_data['absences'] = tidy_data['absences'].astype('int64', errors='ignore')

Analysis and Hypothesis Testing¶

We have quite a few variables which were categorical and had binary responses like: gender (F or M), parent cohabitation status (T for together or A for apart) etc. For these variables, we will conduct hypothesis tests to see if they are significant factors that contribute to average exam score. We will use the two-sample t-test because we don't know the population standard deviation. We will use a significance level of 0.10 rather than the standard 0.05 which increases our probability of a Type I error. To read more about this, please see https://machinelearningmastery.com/parametric-statistical-significance-tests-in-python/

We'll start with gender. First, we'll calculate the average exam score for the males and females to see if they are majorly different:

In [11]:
male_avg = 0
female_avg = 0
male_count = 0
female_count = 0

for i,person in tidy_data.iterrows():
    if person['sex'] == 0:
        male_avg+=person['Average_Score']
        male_count+=1
    elif person['sex'] == 1:
        female_avg+=person['Average_Score']
        female_count+=1
    
male_avg/=male_count
female_avg/=female_count

# Calculating the average scores for both genders
print("Male Avg Scores: " + str(male_avg))
print("Female Avg Scores: " + str(female_avg))

Male Avg Scores: 11.073083779
Female Avg Scores: 10.3253205128

The average score for males is higher than for females but we can't say for sure if this is a significant difference without a formal hypothesis test. We then conduct a two-sample t test to see if there is a significant difference in average exam score between males and females for this population. Note that for this and the following categorical variables, we assume the variances are unequal for the two groups.

In [12]:
def ttest(label):
    no = tidy_data.loc[tidy_data[label] == 0]
    yes = tidy_data.loc[tidy_data[label] == 1]
    no = no.drop(['sex','age','Pstatus','failures','internet','famrel','Avg_Alc_Consumption',
    'studytime', 'paid', 'activities', 'romantic', 'freetime', 'goout', 'higher', 'absences', 'Parent_Education'],axis=1)
    yes = yes.drop(['sex','age','Pstatus','failures','internet','famrel','Avg_Alc_Consumption',
    'studytime', 'paid', 'activities', 'romantic', 'freetime', 'goout', 'higher', 'absences', 'Parent_Education'],axis=1)
    t,p = scipy.stats.ttest_ind(no, yes, axis=0,equal_var=False) #assuming unequal variances between the groups
    print("t-test p value is", float(p))
In [13]:
ttest('sex')

t-test p value is 0.045040833230012865

Our p-value of 0.045 < $ \alpha $ = 0.10 so we reject the null hypothesis that there is no significant difference in average score between males and females. Thus, we conclude that gender is a significant factor for predicting average score. When we later do our linear regression to try to predict average score, we will include gender as an independent variable.

The next categorical variable we tested for significance was parent cohabitation status - 1 for parents live together and 0 for parents live separately.

In [14]:
ttest('Pstatus')

t-test p value is 0.4055887739147568

0.406 > $ \alpha $ = 0.10 so we conclude that the average score is not significantly different between students whose parents live together vs whose parents are separated. So we will not include parent cohabitation status in our linear regression model.

The next categorical variable we tested for significance was paid - 1(Yes) for students who pay for additional tutoring or 0(No).

The next categorical variable we tested for significance was activities - Yes for students who are involved in extracurricular activities or No.

This factor intuitively seems like it should matter; students who have less free time due to extracurricular activities might have less time to study and perform worse than those who aren't in any extracurricular activities. Or, they might be more involved and driven students who still manage to find time to study and thus perform better. We have quite a few numerical variables. Some of them are continuous numerical variables, meaning the measured number can take on any range of values. However, some of them are discrete numerical variables meaning the number is in a fixed range of values. Dealing with variable classification for a dataset is very important as it allows you to decide the best way to analyze or visualize the particular variable. For a more in-depth explanation on types of data/variables, please see http://scaryscientist.blogspot.com/2015/02/classification-of-data-types.html.

Let's look at the discrete numerical variables as they are not as straightforward as our continuous ones. These are the variables that represent a range of responses from 0 to 4 inclusive or 0 to 5 inclusive rather than the value itself having meaning. For example, Medu values range from 0 to 4 with 4 being higher education and 0 being none, while age values are simply the student's age. Here are the discrete numerical variables with range responses repeated from tidy_data and what they represent:

  • Parent_Education - mother and father's education aggregated as an average (numeric: 0 - none, 1 - primary education (4th grade), 2 5th to 9th grade, 3 secondary education or 4 higher education)
  • studytime - weekly study time (numeric: 1 - <2 hours, 2 - 2 to 5 hours, 3 - 5 to 10 hours, or 4 - >10 hours)
  • famrel - quality of family relationships (numeric: from 1 - very bad to 5 - excellent)
  • freetime - free time after school (numeric: from 1 - very low to 5 - very high)
  • goout - going out with friends (numeric: from 1 - very low to 5 - very high)
  • Avg_Alc_Consumption - workday and weekend alcohol consumption aggregated as an average (numeric: from 1 - very low to 5 - very high)
  • absences - number of school absences that we put into bins (numeric: 0 - 0 to 5 absences, 1 - 5 to 10 absences, 2 - 10 to 20 absences, 3 - 20 to 25 absences, 4 - >25 absences)

Machine Learning¶

So now we have our final categorical and numerical variables that we will perform linear regression on to make a predictor model for average exam score. Here is the list of the variables we will use:

Categorical¶

  • Gender (binary; M or F)
  • Paid (binary;pay for tutoring or not)
  • Activities (binary;extracurricular activities or not)
  • Higher (binary;interested in higher education or not)
  • Internet (binary:internet at home or not)
  • Romantic (binary:relationship or not)

Numerical¶

  • Parent_Education (values: 0 to 4)
  • Studytime (values: 0 to 4)
  • Failures (values: 0 to 3)
  • Goout (values: 1 to 5)
  • Avg_Alc_Consumption (values: 1 to 5)
  • Absences (values: 0 to 4)


Let's create a new dataframe that contains only the variables above for our linear regression.

The R-squared value for our first model is 0.212. This means that 21.2% of the variability in our dependent variable Average_Score can be explained by our independent variables. R-squared values range from 0 to 1 and ideally we want it to be as close to 1 as possible. Our adjusted R-squared value is 0.188. Adjusted R-squared modifies the R-squared value to take into account the number of predictors(independent variables) because R-squared always goes up as you add more predictors. So we will focus on the adjusted R-squared value. See http://blog.minitab.com/blog/adventures-in-statistics-2/multiple-regession-analysis-use-adjusted-r-squared-and-predicted-r-squared-to-include-the-correct-number-of-variables for a better explanation and information about analyzing multiple regression models

We then look at the p-values for each independent variable. This tells us how significant the variable is to the model. Paid, activities, and Avg_Alc_Consumption all have large p-values. However, this may be because there are other variables with lower p-values that are already contributing to the model and making these three variables insignificant. Let's make another model taking the paid variable out since it has the largest p-value.

Multiple Linear Regression Model with Logarithmic Transform¶

Although our multiple regression linear model's residual plot met our assumptions, the model itself did not perform that well based on the large residuals meaning it did not predict average score very well. Let's try transforming our response variable by taking the natural logarithm of average score and then running the regressions again. Hopefully this gives us a stronger model. See https://stats.stackexchange.com/questions/298/in-linear-regression-when-is-it-appropriate-to-use-the-log-of-an-independent-va for better insights on when logarithmic transform is an appropriate step to take.

Conclusions¶

The objective of our project was to investigate factors that may affect student exam performance. After going through the entire data analysis, we came to the conclusion that there is no one factor that best predicts exam performance. We started by looking at the correlations between the variables and student's exam scores. However, there were no strong correlations for any of the variables so we then conducted hypothesis tests for the variables to see if there was any significant effect on exam scores. We then applied machine learning by creating multiple linear regression models and then refining the model based on the p-values for each variable. Finally, we tried a log transformation on the response variable of average score to create a new model which slighly improved on our first but still was not very accurate.

If we were to conduct further analysis, we could find other similar datasets and apply what we did here to see if any variables would be more substantial in predicting exam performance. We could also do more in-depth testing on each of the variables in relation to exam scores to try creating a better model. Some things we were interested in but not able to implement were adding cross validation to create a better model and examining the variables more closely for multicollinearity which would negatively impact our model's predictions.
